==Subjective lists==
Several prominent players and writers have attempted to rank the greatest players. Generally these lists attempt to combine the two methods above?performance, and analysis of games.

===Bobby Fischer (1964)===
In 1964 [[Bobby Fischer]] listed his top 10 in Chessworld magazine: [[Paul Morphy|Morphy]], [[Howard Staunton|Staunton]], [[Wilhelm Steinitz|Steinitz]], [[Siegbert Tarrasch|Tarrasch]], [[Mikhail Chigorin|Chigorin]], [[Alexander Alekhine|Alekhine]], [[Jos? Ra?l Capablanca|Capablanca]], [[Boris Spassky|Spassky]], [[Mikhail Tal|Tal]], [[Samuel Reshevsky|Reshevsky]].<ref>Bobby Fischer, "The Ten Greatest Masters in History", ''Chessworld'', Vol. 1, No. 1 (Jan.-Feb. 1964), pp. 56?61.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://chess.eusa.ed.ac.uk/Chess/Trivia/Fishers10.html|title=Fischer's Top 10}}</ref>  He considered Morphy the best, saying "In a set match he would beat anyone alive today."<ref>''the Even More Complete Chess Addict'', by Mike Fox and Richard James, 1993, pp. 129?30</ref>

===Irving Chernev (1976)===
In 1976 chess author [[Irving Chernev]] published the book ''The Golden Dozen'', in which he ranked his all-time top twelve: 1. [[Jos? Ra?l Capablanca|Capablanca]], 2. [[Alexander Alekhine|Alekhine]], 3. [[Emanuel Lasker|Lasker]], 4. [[Bobby Fischer|Fischer]], 5. [[Mikhail Botvinnik|Botvinnik]], 6. [[Tigran Petrosian|Petrosian]], 7. [[Mikhail Tal|Tal]], 8. [[Vasily Smyslov|Smyslov]], 9. [[Boris Spassky|Spassky]], 10. [[David Bronstein|Bronstein]], 11. [[Akiba Rubinstein|Rubinstein]], and 12. [[Aaron Nimzowitsch|Nimzowitsch]].<ref>''Twelve Great Chess Players and Their Best Games'', Irving Chernev, 1995 (reprint of 1976 edition).</ref>

