=== Vladimir Kramnik (2005, 2011) ===
In a 2005 interview, [[Vladimir Kramnik]] (World Champion 2000 to 2007) stated, "The other world champions had something 'missing'. I can't say the same about Kasparov: he can do everything."<ref>http://www.kramnik.com/eng/interviews/getinterview.aspx?id=61</ref>

In an interview in 2011, Vladimir Kramnik said about [[Viswanathan Anand|Anand]]: "I always considered him to be a colossal talent, one of the greatest in the whole history of chess", "I think that in terms of play Anand is in no way weaker than [[Garry Kasparov|Kasparov]]",  and "In the last 5?6 years he's made a qualitative leap that's made it possible to consider him one of the great chess players".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whychess.org/node/1605 |title=Vladimir Kramnik on Chess, Anand, Topalov, and his future | date=2011-08-31}}</ref>

===Leonard Barden (2008)===
In his 2008 obituary of Bobby Fischer, [[Leonard Barden]] wrote that most experts ranked Kasparov as the greatest ever, with either Fischer or Karpov second.<ref>"''Most experts place him (Fischer) the second or third best ever, behind Kasparov but probably ahead of Karpov.''" ? [http://www.guardian.co.uk/obituaries/story/0,,2243266,00.html Obituary of Bobby Fischer], [[Leonard Barden]], [[The Guardian]], 19 January 2008</ref>

=== Levon Aronian (2012) ===
In a 2012 interview, [[Levon Aronian]] stated that he considers Alexander Alekhine the greatest player of all time.<ref>http://whychess.com/en/node/2836</ref>

=== Magnus Carlsen (2012) ===
In 2012, [[Magnus Carlsen]] said that Kasparov is the greatest player of all time, saying that while Fischer may have been better at his best, Kasparov remained at the top for much longer.<ref>http://www.vg.no/sport/artikkel.php?artid=10060899</ref>

